l. 122. Idomenea, an Homeric acc. (εἸδομενῆα) Idomeneus accompanied the Greeks to Troy with ninety ships. On his return he made a vow to Neptune during a dangerous tempest that if he escaped he would offer to the god the first living creature that met him on landing on the shore of Crete. This proved to be his own son. Idomeneus performed his promise, but his inhumanity made him so odious that he was driven from the country. Cp. Jephtha's rash vow.
